Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? Let‚Äôs discuss! üöÄhashtag#ASPNetCore hashtag#Authorization hashtag#Security hashtag#Coding hashtag#CustomAttributes

In this series, I‚Äôll uncover some hidden gems in .NET that can make your code faster, cleaner, and more efficient. Let‚Äôs start with a simple but powerful one: Lazy<T>.üí°ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùó∂ùòÄ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ ùóúùóªùó∂ùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª?Normally, we initialize objects as soon as we declare them, but what if we don‚Äôt always need them? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! In the next article, we‚Äôll explore other hidden gem for high-performance memory handling.Have you used Lazy<T> before? Let me know in the comments! üí¨

You don‚Äôt need to know everything about AWS, but you should know this.Many people get stuck when starting with AWS because they think they need to master all 200+ services before deploying something to production.The truth? Most web applications use fewer than 10 services.If I had to relearn AWS in a more productive way‚Äîbeyond just reading the docs and taking AWS courses‚ÄîI would focus on these:‚úÖ EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Scalable virtual machines that provide computing power to run applications, offering flexibility in instance types, storage, and networking.‚úÖ ECS (Elastic Container Service) with Fargate ‚Äì A managed container orchestration service that allows you to run Docker containers without provisioning or managing servers, simplifying deployment and scaling.‚úÖ S3 (Simple Storage Service) ‚Äì Highly durable and scalable object storage designed for storing and retrieving files, backups, and static content, with built-in security and lifecycle policies.‚úÖ RDS (Relational Database Service) / DynamoDB ‚Äì RDS provides managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.), while DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database optimized for high-performance and scalable applications.‚úÖ Lambda ‚Äì A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events (like API requests or file uploads) without the need to manage infrastructure, charging only for execution time.‚úÖ API Gateway ‚Äì A fully managed service that enables developers to create, deploy, and secure APIs at scale, integrating seamlessly with Lambda, EC2, and other AWS services.‚úÖ CloudWatch ‚Äì A monitoring and observability service that collects logs, metrics, and events from AWS resources, enabling real-time insights, alerting, and troubleshooting.‚úÖ IAM (Identity and Access Management) ‚Äì AWS‚Äôs security framework for managing users, roles, and permissions to control access to AWS resources. Misconfigurations here can lead to serious security risks.‚úÖ SNS (Simple Notification Service) / SQS (Simple Queue Service) ‚Äì SNS is a pub/sub messaging service for sending notifications, while SQS provides message queuing for decoupling and scaling microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.Master these, and you‚Äôll solve 90% of AWS-related problems without needing to memorize everything.AWS is huge, but you don‚Äôt need to know it all to be effective. Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? In this series, I‚Äôll uncover some hidden gems in .NET that can make your code faster, cleaner, and more efficient. Let‚Äôs start with a simple but powerful one: Lazy<T>.üí°ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùó∂ùòÄ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ ùóúùóªùó∂ùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª?Normally, we initialize objects as soon as we declare them, but what if we don‚Äôt always need them? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! You don‚Äôt need to know everything about AWS, but you should know this.Many people get stuck when starting with AWS because they think they need to master all 200+ services before deploying something to production.The truth? Most web applications use fewer than 10 services.If I had to relearn AWS in a more productive way‚Äîbeyond just reading the docs and taking AWS courses‚ÄîI would focus on these:‚úÖ EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Scalable virtual machines that provide computing power to run applications, offering flexibility in instance types, storage, and networking.‚úÖ ECS (Elastic Container Service) with Fargate ‚Äì A managed container orchestration service that allows you to run Docker containers without provisioning or managing servers, simplifying deployment and scaling.‚úÖ S3 (Simple Storage Service) ‚Äì Highly durable and scalable object storage designed for storing and retrieving files, backups, and static content, with built-in security and lifecycle policies.‚úÖ RDS (Relational Database Service) / DynamoDB ‚Äì RDS provides managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.), while DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database optimized for high-performance and scalable applications.‚úÖ Lambda ‚Äì A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events (like API requests or file uploads) without the need to manage infrastructure, charging only for execution time.‚úÖ API Gateway ‚Äì A fully managed service that enables developers to create, deploy, and secure APIs at scale, integrating seamlessly with Lambda, EC2, and other AWS services.‚úÖ CloudWatch ‚Äì A monitoring and observability service that collects logs, metrics, and events from AWS resources, enabling real-time insights, alerting, and troubleshooting.‚úÖ IAM (Identity and Access Management) ‚Äì AWS‚Äôs security framework for managing users, roles, and permissions to control access to AWS resources. Misconfigurations here can lead to serious security risks.‚úÖ SNS (Simple Notification Service) / SQS (Simple Queue Service) ‚Äì SNS is a pub/sub messaging service for sending notifications, while SQS provides message queuing for decoupling and scaling microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.Master these, and you‚Äôll solve 90% of AWS-related problems without needing to memorize everything.AWS is huge, but you don‚Äôt need to know it all to be effective. Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? Let‚Äôs discuss! üöÄhashtag#ASPNetCore hashtag#Authorization hashtag#Security hashtag#Coding hashtag#CustomAttributes

In this series, I‚Äôll uncover some hidden gems in .NET that can make your code faster, cleaner, and more efficient. Let‚Äôs start with a simple but powerful one: Lazy<T>.üí°ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùó∂ùòÄ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ ùóúùóªùó∂ùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª?Normally, we initialize objects as soon as we declare them, but what if we don‚Äôt always need them? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! You don‚Äôt need to know everything about AWS, but you should know this.Many people get stuck when starting with AWS because they think they need to master all 200+ services before deploying something to production.The truth? Most web applications use fewer than 10 services.If I had to relearn AWS in a more productive way‚Äîbeyond just reading the docs and taking AWS courses‚ÄîI would focus on these:‚úÖ EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Scalable virtual machines that provide computing power to run applications, offering flexibility in instance types, storage, and networking.‚úÖ ECS (Elastic Container Service) with Fargate ‚Äì A managed container orchestration service that allows you to run Docker containers without provisioning or managing servers, simplifying deployment and scaling.‚úÖ S3 (Simple Storage Service) ‚Äì Highly durable and scalable object storage designed for storing and retrieving files, backups, and static content, with built-in security and lifecycle policies.‚úÖ RDS (Relational Database Service) / DynamoDB ‚Äì RDS provides managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.), while DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database optimized for high-performance and scalable applications.‚úÖ Lambda ‚Äì A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events (like API requests or file uploads) without the need to manage infrastructure, charging only for execution time.‚úÖ API Gateway ‚Äì A fully managed service that enables developers to create, deploy, and secure APIs at scale, integrating seamlessly with Lambda, EC2, and other AWS services.‚úÖ CloudWatch ‚Äì A monitoring and observability service that collects logs, metrics, and events from AWS resources, enabling real-time insights, alerting, and troubleshooting.‚úÖ IAM (Identity and Access Management) ‚Äì AWS‚Äôs security framework for managing users, roles, and permissions to control access to AWS resources. Misconfigurations here can lead to serious security risks.‚úÖ SNS (Simple Notification Service) / SQS (Simple Queue Service) ‚Äì SNS is a pub/sub messaging service for sending notifications, while SQS provides message queuing for decoupling and scaling microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.Master these, and you‚Äôll solve 90% of AWS-related problems without needing to memorize everything.AWS is huge, but you don‚Äôt need to know it all to be effective. Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? In this series, I‚Äôll uncover some hidden gems in .NET that can make your code faster, cleaner, and more efficient. Let‚Äôs start with a simple but powerful one: Lazy<T>.üí°ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùó∂ùòÄ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ ùóúùóªùó∂ùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª?Normally, we initialize objects as soon as we declare them, but what if we don‚Äôt always need them? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! You don‚Äôt need to know everything about AWS, but you should know this.Many people get stuck when starting with AWS because they think they need to master all 200+ services before deploying something to production.The truth? Most web applications use fewer than 10 services.If I had to relearn AWS in a more productive way‚Äîbeyond just reading the docs and taking AWS courses‚ÄîI would focus on these:‚úÖ EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Scalable virtual machines that provide computing power to run applications, offering flexibility in instance types, storage, and networking.‚úÖ ECS (Elastic Container Service) with Fargate ‚Äì A managed container orchestration service that allows you to run Docker containers without provisioning or managing servers, simplifying deployment and scaling.‚úÖ S3 (Simple Storage Service) ‚Äì Highly durable and scalable object storage designed for storing and retrieving files, backups, and static content, with built-in security and lifecycle policies.‚úÖ RDS (Relational Database Service) / DynamoDB ‚Äì RDS provides managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.), while DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database optimized for high-performance and scalable applications.‚úÖ Lambda ‚Äì A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events (like API requests or file uploads) without the need to manage infrastructure, charging only for execution time.‚úÖ API Gateway ‚Äì A fully managed service that enables developers to create, deploy, and secure APIs at scale, integrating seamlessly with Lambda, EC2, and other AWS services.‚úÖ CloudWatch ‚Äì A monitoring and observability service that collects logs, metrics, and events from AWS resources, enabling real-time insights, alerting, and troubleshooting.‚úÖ IAM (Identity and Access Management) ‚Äì AWS‚Äôs security framework for managing users, roles, and permissions to control access to AWS resources. Misconfigurations here can lead to serious security risks.‚úÖ SNS (Simple Notification Service) / SQS (Simple Queue Service) ‚Äì SNS is a pub/sub messaging service for sending notifications, while SQS provides message queuing for decoupling and scaling microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.Master these, and you‚Äôll solve 90% of AWS-related problems without needing to memorize everything.AWS is huge, but you don‚Äôt need to know it all to be effective. Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? Let‚Äôs discuss! üöÄhashtag#ASPNetCore hashtag#Authorization hashtag#Security hashtag#Coding hashtag#CustomAttributes

In this series, I‚Äôll uncover some hidden gems in .NET that can make your code faster, cleaner, and more efficient. Let‚Äôs start with a simple but powerful one: Lazy<T>.üí°ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùó∂ùòÄ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ ùóúùóªùó∂ùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª?Normally, we initialize objects as soon as we declare them, but what if we don‚Äôt always need them? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! You don‚Äôt need to know everything about AWS, but you should know this.Many people get stuck when starting with AWS because they think they need to master all 200+ services before deploying something to production.The truth? Most web applications use fewer than 10 services.If I had to relearn AWS in a more productive way‚Äîbeyond just reading the docs and taking AWS courses‚ÄîI would focus on these:‚úÖ EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Scalable virtual machines that provide computing power to run applications, offering flexibility in instance types, storage, and networking.‚úÖ ECS (Elastic Container Service) with Fargate ‚Äì A managed container orchestration service that allows you to run Docker containers without provisioning or managing servers, simplifying deployment and scaling.‚úÖ S3 (Simple Storage Service) ‚Äì Highly durable and scalable object storage designed for storing and retrieving files, backups, and static content, with built-in security and lifecycle policies.‚úÖ RDS (Relational Database Service) / DynamoDB ‚Äì RDS provides managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.), while DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database optimized for high-performance and scalable applications.‚úÖ Lambda ‚Äì A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events (like API requests or file uploads) without the need to manage infrastructure, charging only for execution time.‚úÖ API Gateway ‚Äì A fully managed service that enables developers to create, deploy, and secure APIs at scale, integrating seamlessly with Lambda, EC2, and other AWS services.‚úÖ CloudWatch ‚Äì A monitoring and observability service that collects logs, metrics, and events from AWS resources, enabling real-time insights, alerting, and troubleshooting.‚úÖ IAM (Identity and Access Management) ‚Äì AWS‚Äôs security framework for managing users, roles, and permissions to control access to AWS resources. Misconfigurations here can lead to serious security risks.‚úÖ SNS (Simple Notification Service) / SQS (Simple Queue Service) ‚Äì SNS is a pub/sub messaging service for sending notifications, while SQS provides message queuing for decoupling and scaling microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.Master these, and you‚Äôll solve 90% of AWS-related problems without needing to memorize everything.AWS is huge, but you don‚Äôt need to know it all to be effective. Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? Let‚Äôs discuss! üöÄhashtag#ASPNetCore hashtag#Authorization hashtag#Security hashtag#Coding hashtag#CustomAttributes

In this series, I‚Äôll uncover some hidden gems in .NET that can make your code faster, cleaner, and more efficient. Let‚Äôs start with a simple but powerful one: Lazy<T>.üí°ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùó∂ùòÄ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ ùóúùóªùó∂ùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª?Normally, we initialize objects as soon as we declare them, but what if we don‚Äôt always need them? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! In the next article, we‚Äôll explore other hidden gem for high-performance memory handling.Have you used Lazy<T> before? Let me know in the comments! üí¨

You don‚Äôt need to know everything about AWS, but you should know this.Many people get stuck when starting with AWS because they think they need to master all 200+ services before deploying something to production.The truth? Most web applications use fewer than 10 services.If I had to relearn AWS in a more productive way‚Äîbeyond just reading the docs and taking AWS courses‚ÄîI would focus on these:‚úÖ EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Scalable virtual machines that provide computing power to run applications, offering flexibility in instance types, storage, and networking.‚úÖ ECS (Elastic Container Service) with Fargate ‚Äì A managed container orchestration service that allows you to run Docker containers without provisioning or managing servers, simplifying deployment and scaling.‚úÖ S3 (Simple Storage Service) ‚Äì Highly durable and scalable object storage designed for storing and retrieving files, backups, and static content, with built-in security and lifecycle policies.‚úÖ RDS (Relational Database Service) / DynamoDB ‚Äì RDS provides managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.), while DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database optimized for high-performance and scalable applications.‚úÖ Lambda ‚Äì A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events (like API requests or file uploads) without the need to manage infrastructure, charging only for execution time.‚úÖ API Gateway ‚Äì A fully managed service that enables developers to create, deploy, and secure APIs at scale, integrating seamlessly with Lambda, EC2, and other AWS services.‚úÖ CloudWatch ‚Äì A monitoring and observability service that collects logs, metrics, and events from AWS resources, enabling real-time insights, alerting, and troubleshooting.‚úÖ IAM (Identity and Access Management) ‚Äì AWS‚Äôs security framework for managing users, roles, and permissions to control access to AWS resources. Misconfigurations here can lead to serious security risks.‚úÖ SNS (Simple Notification Service) / SQS (Simple Queue Service) ‚Äì SNS is a pub/sub messaging service for sending notifications, while SQS provides message queuing for decoupling and scaling microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.Master these, and you‚Äôll solve 90% of AWS-related problems without needing to memorize everything.AWS is huge, but you don‚Äôt need to know it all to be effective. Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? In this series, I‚Äôll uncover some hidden gems in .NET that can make your code faster, cleaner, and more efficient. Let‚Äôs start with a simple but powerful one: Lazy<T>.üí°ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùó∂ùòÄ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ ùóúùóªùó∂ùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª?Normally, we initialize objects as soon as we declare them, but what if we don‚Äôt always need them? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! You don‚Äôt need to know everything about AWS, but you should know this.Many people get stuck when starting with AWS because they think they need to master all 200+ services before deploying something to production.The truth? Most web applications use fewer than 10 services.If I had to relearn AWS in a more productive way‚Äîbeyond just reading the docs and taking AWS courses‚ÄîI would focus on these:‚úÖ EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Scalable virtual machines that provide computing power to run applications, offering flexibility in instance types, storage, and networking.‚úÖ ECS (Elastic Container Service) with Fargate ‚Äì A managed container orchestration service that allows you to run Docker containers without provisioning or managing servers, simplifying deployment and scaling.‚úÖ S3 (Simple Storage Service) ‚Äì Highly durable and scalable object storage designed for storing and retrieving files, backups, and static content, with built-in security and lifecycle policies.‚úÖ RDS (Relational Database Service) / DynamoDB ‚Äì RDS provides managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.), while DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database optimized for high-performance and scalable applications.‚úÖ Lambda ‚Äì A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events (like API requests or file uploads) without the need to manage infrastructure, charging only for execution time.‚úÖ API Gateway ‚Äì A fully managed service that enables developers to create, deploy, and secure APIs at scale, integrating seamlessly with Lambda, EC2, and other AWS services.‚úÖ CloudWatch ‚Äì A monitoring and observability service that collects logs, metrics, and events from AWS resources, enabling real-time insights, alerting, and troubleshooting.‚úÖ IAM (Identity and Access Management) ‚Äì AWS‚Äôs security framework for managing users, roles, and permissions to control access to AWS resources. Misconfigurations here can lead to serious security risks.‚úÖ SNS (Simple Notification Service) / SQS (Simple Queue Service) ‚Äì SNS is a pub/sub messaging service for sending notifications, while SQS provides message queuing for decoupling and scaling microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.Master these, and you‚Äôll solve 90% of AWS-related problems without needing to memorize everything.AWS is huge, but you don‚Äôt need to know it all to be effective. Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? Let‚Äôs start with a simple but powerful one: Lazy<T>.üí°ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùó∂ùòÄ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ ùóúùóªùó∂ùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª?Normally, we initialize objects as soon as we declare them, but what if we don‚Äôt always need them? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! You don‚Äôt need to know everything about AWS, but you should know this.Many people get stuck when starting with AWS because they think they need to master all 200+ services before deploying something to production.The truth? Most web applications use fewer than 10 services.If I had to relearn AWS in a more productive way‚Äîbeyond just reading the docs and taking AWS courses‚ÄîI would focus on these:‚úÖ EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Scalable virtual machines that provide computing power to run applications, offering flexibility in instance types, storage, and networking.‚úÖ ECS (Elastic Container Service) with Fargate ‚Äì A managed container orchestration service that allows you to run Docker containers without provisioning or managing servers, simplifying deployment and scaling.‚úÖ S3 (Simple Storage Service) ‚Äì Highly durable and scalable object storage designed for storing and retrieving files, backups, and static content, with built-in security and lifecycle policies.‚úÖ RDS (Relational Database Service) / DynamoDB ‚Äì RDS provides managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.), while DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database optimized for high-performance and scalable applications.‚úÖ Lambda ‚Äì A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events (like API requests or file uploads) without the need to manage infrastructure, charging only for execution time.‚úÖ API Gateway ‚Äì A fully managed service that enables developers to create, deploy, and secure APIs at scale, integrating seamlessly with Lambda, EC2, and other AWS services.‚úÖ CloudWatch ‚Äì A monitoring and observability service that collects logs, metrics, and events from AWS resources, enabling real-time insights, alerting, and troubleshooting.‚úÖ IAM (Identity and Access Management) ‚Äì AWS‚Äôs security framework for managing users, roles, and permissions to control access to AWS resources. Misconfigurations here can lead to serious security risks.‚úÖ SNS (Simple Notification Service) / SQS (Simple Queue Service) ‚Äì SNS is a pub/sub messaging service for sending notifications, while SQS provides message queuing for decoupling and scaling microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.Master these, and you‚Äôll solve 90% of AWS-related problems without needing to memorize everything.AWS is huge, but you don‚Äôt need to know it all to be effective. Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? Let‚Äôs start with a simple but powerful one: Lazy<T>.üí°ùó™ùóµùóÆùòÅ ùó∂ùòÄ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ ùóúùóªùó∂ùòÅùó∂ùóÆùóπùó∂ùòáùóÆùòÅùó∂ùóºùóª?Normally, we initialize objects as soon as we declare them, but what if we don‚Äôt always need them? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! You don‚Äôt need to know everything about AWS, but you should know this.Many people get stuck when starting with AWS because they think they need to master all 200+ services before deploying something to production.The truth? Most web applications use fewer than 10 services.If I had to relearn AWS in a more productive way‚Äîbeyond just reading the docs and taking AWS courses‚ÄîI would focus on these:‚úÖ EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Scalable virtual machines that provide computing power to run applications, offering flexibility in instance types, storage, and networking.‚úÖ ECS (Elastic Container Service) with Fargate ‚Äì A managed container orchestration service that allows you to run Docker containers without provisioning or managing servers, simplifying deployment and scaling.‚úÖ S3 (Simple Storage Service) ‚Äì Highly durable and scalable object storage designed for storing and retrieving files, backups, and static content, with built-in security and lifecycle policies.‚úÖ RDS (Relational Database Service) / DynamoDB ‚Äì RDS provides managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server, etc.), while DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database optimized for high-performance and scalable applications.‚úÖ Lambda ‚Äì A serverless compute service that runs code in response to events (like API requests or file uploads) without the need to manage infrastructure, charging only for execution time.‚úÖ API Gateway ‚Äì A fully managed service that enables developers to create, deploy, and secure APIs at scale, integrating seamlessly with Lambda, EC2, and other AWS services.‚úÖ CloudWatch ‚Äì A monitoring and observability service that collects logs, metrics, and events from AWS resources, enabling real-time insights, alerting, and troubleshooting.‚úÖ IAM (Identity and Access Management) ‚Äì AWS‚Äôs security framework for managing users, roles, and permissions to control access to AWS resources. Misconfigurations here can lead to serious security risks.‚úÖ SNS (Simple Notification Service) / SQS (Simple Queue Service) ‚Äì SNS is a pub/sub messaging service for sending notifications, while SQS provides message queuing for decoupling and scaling microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications.Master these, and you‚Äôll solve 90% of AWS-related problems without needing to memorize everything.AWS is huge, but you don‚Äôt need to know it all to be effective. Enhancing Authorization with a Custom Attribute in ASP.NET CoreChecking roles like "Admin" isn‚Äôt always enough for security. What if you need to ensure only certain admins can access specific endpoints? A better approach is combining roles + permissions for fine-grained control.How to Do It?By creating a custom authorization attribute that: ‚úÖ Checks if the user is authenticated ‚úÖ Verifies their role (e.g., Admin) ‚úÖ Ensures they have the correct permission (e.g., "CanAccessAdminPanel")Example Implementation:A simple custom attribute to enforce role and permission validation:csharpCopyEditpublic class CustomAuthorizeAttribute : Attribute, IAsyncActionFilter{ private readonly string _requiredRole; private readonly string _requiredPermission; public CustomAuthorizeAttribute(string requiredRole, string requiredPermission) { _requiredRole = requiredRole; _requiredPermission = requiredPermission; } public async Task OnActionExecutionAsync(ActionExecutingContext context, ActionExecutionDelegate next) { if (!context.HttpContext.User.Identity.IsAuthenticated) { context.Result = new UnauthorizedResult(); return; } if (!context.HttpContext.User.IsInRole(_requiredRole)) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } var hasPermission = context.HttpContext.User.Claims.Any(c =>  c.Type == "Permission" && c.Value == _requiredPermission);  if (!hasPermission) { context.Result = new ForbidResult(); return; } await next(); }}How It Works?üîπ Authentication Check: Ensures the user is logged in. üîπ Role Check: Verifies the user‚Äôs role (e.g., Admin). üîπ Permission Check: Confirms they have the required permission. üîπ Proceed or Block: If any check fails, access is denied.This ensures not all admins get full access‚Äîonly those with the right permissions do.Would you use this approach in your project? Lazy<T> ensures an object is only created when first accessed, avoiding unnecessary memory usage.Instead of this:‚ùåMyClass obj = new MyClass(); // Created immediately You can use:‚úÖLazy<MyClass> obj = new Lazy<MyClass>(() => new MyClass()); Now, obj.Value will only be created when needed! üéØüí°ùó™ùóµùòÜ ùó¶ùóµùóºùòÇùóπùó± ùó¨ùóºùòÇ ùó®ùòÄùó≤ ùóüùóÆùòáùòÜ<T>?If your object is expensive to create (e.g., loading a large dataset), Lazy<T> improves performance by delaying initialization until it's truly required. It's also thread-safe by default, making it great for multithreaded applications.This is just the beginning! In the next article, we‚Äôll explore other hidden gem for high-performance memory handling.Have you used Lazy<T> before? Let me know in the comments! üí¨
